    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips. if it is nitrogen deficiency, what should i do to fix it? also how do i know if my soil ph is messed up? i dont have a kit so i'm kind of guessing",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you suspect a nitrogen deficiency, you'll want to give your tomato plants a boost of nitrogen, which is the 'N' in NPK. You could use a balanced, slow-release organic fertilizer, or if you want a quick fix, a liquid fish emulsion or a diluted blood meal can work wonders. For the soil pH, since you don't have a kit, you're essentially relying on guesswork, which is risky, but you can look for telltale signs. If your soil is too acidic, you might see stunted growth and some nutrient lockout, which is a real pain, and you might need to add lime. If it's too alkaline, you might need sulfur. It's a bit like trying to navigate a maze in the dark, but a quick, cheap soil test kit from a garden center is the best way to get a real answer.",
      "source": "target",
